    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Now, if you’re unfamiliar with this, the idea is that it’s not geometrically easy to find this area. We resort to mathematical formulations instead. It’s the same as splitting the area under our curve into infinitely many rectangles and adding all their areas up. Something like this:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:64%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 482px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*iAhqvaidLESBHpOl.gif 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*iAhqvaidLESBHpOl.gif 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*iAhqvaidLESBHpOl.gif 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*iAhqvaidLESBHpOl.gif 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*iAhqvaidLESBHpOl.gif 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*iAhqvaidLESBHpOl.gif 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:964/0*iAhqvaidLESBHpOl.gif 964w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 482px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*iAhqvaidLESBHpOl.gif 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*iAhqvaidLESBHpOl.gif 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*iAhqvaidLESBHpOl.gif 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*iAhqvaidLESBHpOl.gif 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*iAhqvaidLESBHpOl.gif 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*iAhqvaidLESBHpOl.gif 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:964/0*iAhqvaidLESBHpOl.gif 964w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:482/0*iAhqvaidLESBHpOl.gif"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">A visual perspective to integration. Wikimedia commons.</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Now, the delta function is specially defined so that its integral is equal to one. Over all space, you find that the area bound by the delta function and the <em>x-axis</em> is one.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:66%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 493px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*7EtOLxN3EjS5gjBVrRMSiA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*7EtOLxN3EjS5gjBVrRMSiA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*7EtOLxN3EjS5gjBVrRMSiA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*7EtOLxN3EjS5gjBVrRMSiA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*7EtOLxN3EjS5gjBVrRMSiA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*7EtOLxN3EjS5gjBVrRMSiA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:986/format:webp/1*7EtOLxN3EjS5gjBVrRMSiA.png 986w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 493px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*7EtOLxN3EjS5gjBVrRMSiA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*7EtOLxN3EjS5gjBVrRMSiA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*7EtOLxN3EjS5gjBVrRMSiA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*7EtOLxN3EjS5gjBVrRMSiA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*7EtOLxN3EjS5gjBVrRMSiA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*7EtOLxN3EjS5gjBVrRMSiA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:986/1*7EtOLxN3EjS5gjBVrRMSiA.png 986w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:493/1*7EtOLxN3EjS5gjBVrRMSiA.png"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">This is incredibly strange to think about considering there is no area under the graph anywhere except for where x = 0. The width of this function is zero and the height is infinite and yet somehow the area under this function happens to be finite: 1. If you want to know more about this, feel free to google it. This is merely a property of the Dirac delta; we’d digress if we got into the math of it all. For what it’s worth, take me on blind faith with this one.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Now there’s another intricacy here. The delta function does not need to spike specifically at <em>x = </em>0<em>. </em>We can move this function around to spike at exactly what we’d like. If you’re familiar with translating functions, you’d know that if you took some dependent variable, <em>x,</em> and subtracted some quantity from it, let’s say <em>a,</em> then what you’re doing is actually shifting the entire graph rightwards by <em>a</em> units.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*W9U62ram4fC3yTEhTk1-YQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*W9U62ram4fC3yTEhTk1-YQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*W9U62ram4fC3yTEhTk1-YQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*W9U62ram4fC3yTEhTk1-YQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*W9U62ram4fC3yTEhTk1-YQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*W9U62ram4fC3yTEhTk1-YQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*W9U62ram4fC3yTEhTk1-YQ.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*W9U62ram4fC3yTEhTk1-YQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*W9U62ram4fC3yTEhTk1-YQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*W9U62ram4fC3yTEhTk1-YQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*W9U62ram4fC3yTEhTk1-YQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*W9U62ram4fC3yTEhTk1-YQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*W9U62ram4fC3yTEhTk1-YQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*W9U62ram4fC3yTEhTk1-YQ.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/1*W9U62ram4fC3yTEhTk1-YQ.png"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">We could do the same with the delta function if we wanted to.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*-ESRH_Fxc015Xuh3EIfuTQ.jpeg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*-ESRH_Fxc015Xuh3EIfuTQ.jpeg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*-ESRH_Fxc015Xuh3EIfuTQ.jpeg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*-ESRH_Fxc015Xuh3EIfuTQ.jpeg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*-ESRH_Fxc015Xuh3EIfuTQ.jpeg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*-ESRH_Fxc015Xuh3EIfuTQ.jpeg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*-ESRH_Fxc015Xuh3EIfuTQ.jpeg 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*-ESRH_Fxc015Xuh3EIfuTQ.jpeg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*-ESRH_Fxc015Xuh3EIfuTQ.jpeg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*-ESRH_Fxc015Xuh3EIfuTQ.jpeg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*-ESRH_Fxc015Xuh3EIfuTQ.jpeg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*-ESRH_Fxc015Xuh3EIfuTQ.jpeg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*-ESRH_Fxc015Xuh3EIfuTQ.jpeg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*-ESRH_Fxc015Xuh3EIfuTQ.jpeg 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/1*-ESRH_Fxc015Xuh3EIfuTQ.jpeg"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">δ(<em>x) and </em>δ(<em>x-a)</em></p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The reason this is important is that we can now take another function, let’s say the sine function, and multiply it by δ(<em>x-a</em>)<em>. </em>Then, if we were to integrate this, we’d end up with the value of the function — sin(x) in this case — at the point <em>x</em> = <em>a.</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/0*3jf82liDR6Tpc854.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/0*3jf82liDR6Tpc854.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/0*3jf82liDR6Tpc854.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/0*3jf82liDR6Tpc854.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/0*3jf82liDR6Tpc854.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/0*3jf82liDR6Tpc854.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/0*3jf82liDR6Tpc854.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*3jf82liDR6Tpc854.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*3jf82liDR6Tpc854.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*3jf82liDR6Tpc854.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*3jf82liDR6Tpc854.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*3jf82liDR6Tpc854.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*3jf82liDR6Tpc854.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*3jf82liDR6Tpc854.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/0*3jf82liDR6Tpc854.png"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In other words, when used in this way, the delta function can be used to “pick out” values of any function. But this is how far the math goes.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">The Physics</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The delta function is more than just mere mathematical intricacies that make our lives easier. Of course, with this comes a quite important question: “how does an infinitely narrow and infinitely high function help us describe anything real?”.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Well, even though these sorts of infinities don’t show up in our lives, theoretical physics is full of them. To keep things simple, we often treat particles as point masses. We assume that the mass of small particles — like electrons — is concentrated at a point. By definition, a point has no size. It is infinitesimally small.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Consequently, we often treat charged particles as “point” charges. The source is a mere point in space. Call it a pixel if you’d like. We say that their charge is localized to that point. This makes the math a whole lot easier as opposed to considering a distribution of charges over finite space. We just say it’s shoved into a very, very, very narrow area. But where does the Dirac delta come into this?</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">We can start by thinking not about the charge of the particle but rather the <strong>charge density </strong>of the system we’re considering.<strong> </strong>Charge density is simply a quantity that represents the amount of charge we find per unit volume. To put it in a slightly more “correct” way, it’s actually the rate of change of charge with respect to volume.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:30%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 239px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*mSXSsphqCRrSx_ptA2FMwg.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*mSXSsphqCRrSx_ptA2FMwg.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*mSXSsphqCRrSx_ptA2FMwg.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*mSXSsphqCRrSx_ptA2FMwg.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*mSXSsphqCRrSx_ptA2FMwg.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*mSXSsphqCRrSx_ptA2FMwg.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:478/format:webp/1*mSXSsphqCRrSx_ptA2FMwg.png 478w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 239px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*mSXSsphqCRrSx_ptA2FMwg.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*mSXSsphqCRrSx_ptA2FMwg.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*mSXSsphqCRrSx_ptA2FMwg.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*mSXSsphqCRrSx_ptA2FMwg.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*mSXSsphqCRrSx_ptA2FMwg.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*mSXSsphqCRrSx_ptA2FMwg.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:478/1*mSXSsphqCRrSx_ptA2FMwg.png 478w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:239/1*mSXSsphqCRrSx_ptA2FMwg.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Mathematically, this is simply the derivative of the charge with respect to volume.</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Rearranging this to find the charge of the particle, we find that q is simply the integral of density, rho, with respect to volume:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:46%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 352px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*pHx0Wo7R_2e3JXhk_feOxw.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*pHx0Wo7R_2e3JXhk_feOxw.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*pHx0Wo7R_2e3JXhk_feOxw.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*pHx0Wo7R_2e3JXhk_feOxw.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*pHx0Wo7R_2e3JXhk_feOxw.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*pHx0Wo7R_2e3JXhk_feOxw.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:704/format:webp/1*pHx0Wo7R_2e3JXhk_feOxw.png 704w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 352px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*pHx0Wo7R_2e3JXhk_feOxw.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*pHx0Wo7R_2e3JXhk_feOxw.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*pHx0Wo7R_2e3JXhk_feOxw.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*pHx0Wo7R_2e3JXhk_feOxw.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*pHx0Wo7R_2e3JXhk_feOxw.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*pHx0Wo7R_2e3JXhk_feOxw.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:704/1*pHx0Wo7R_2e3JXhk_feOxw.png 704w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:352/1*pHx0Wo7R_2e3JXhk_feOxw.png"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">This is essentially the opposite of taking the derivative. Multiply both sides by dV and take the integral on both sides. There, you have it. Now, the physical interpretation of this is that the charge of the particle can be found by knowing how much charge there is for every <em>tiny </em>bit of volume. We get the charge density and multiply it by the tiny bit of volume to find the tiny bit of charge in that volume. It’s a little weird to explain this in words so we’ll just resort to math instead, <strong>dq = ρdV.</strong></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">We add up all tiny little dqs to give us q. But if you recall, for a point mass, we assume that the charge is not distributed at all. Instead, it’s all found in one single point. Let’s say, <em>x = b</em>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">To keep things simple, we’ll seek refuge in a one-dimensional system. In principle, you can apply the same idea to both the y and z coordinates too. Here’s what we do: we say that the charge density is equal to the charge localized at the point multiplied by the delta function of <em>x-b:</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:60%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 449px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*CPsllZmusQewXl72YzrqsA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*CPsllZmusQewXl72YzrqsA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*CPsllZmusQewXl72YzrqsA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*CPsllZmusQewXl72YzrqsA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*CPsllZmusQewXl72YzrqsA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*CPsllZmusQewXl72YzrqsA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:898/format:webp/1*CPsllZmusQewXl72YzrqsA.png 898w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 449px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*CPsllZmusQewXl72YzrqsA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*CPsllZmusQewXl72YzrqsA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*CPsllZmusQewXl72YzrqsA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*CPsllZmusQewXl72YzrqsA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*CPsllZmusQewXl72YzrqsA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*CPsllZmusQewXl72YzrqsA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:898/1*CPsllZmusQewXl72YzrqsA.png 898w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:449/1*CPsllZmusQewXl72YzrqsA.png"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Why is this useful? Well, check this out. Substituting it back into our equation where q is the integral of rho dV, we get this:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:66%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 491px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*ot-7urkZEvD_eFPWjIfiKw.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*ot-7urkZEvD_eFPWjIfiKw.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*ot-7urkZEvD_eFPWjIfiKw.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*ot-7urkZEvD_eFPWjIfiKw.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*ot-7urkZEvD_eFPWjIfiKw.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*ot-7urkZEvD_eFPWjIfiKw.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:982/format:webp/1*ot-7urkZEvD_eFPWjIfiKw.png 982w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 491px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*ot-7urkZEvD_eFPWjIfiKw.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*ot-7urkZEvD_eFPWjIfiKw.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*ot-7urkZEvD_eFPWjIfiKw.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*ot-7urkZEvD_eFPWjIfiKw.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*ot-7urkZEvD_eFPWjIfiKw.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*ot-7urkZEvD_eFPWjIfiKw.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:982/1*ot-7urkZEvD_eFPWjIfiKw.png 982w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:491/1*ot-7urkZEvD_eFPWjIfiKw.png"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Where q1is simply the magnitude of our point charge. Once again, this is not quite correct because we’re ignoring y and z but let’s stick to this. Earlier, we said that the delta function picks out a value of another function. Well, in this case, q1 is that function. Mathematically, if we were to encode q1, then it would simply be a constant function. But the delta function helps us pick it out at the point in space where the charged particle is located. Once again, I’d like to clarify that the delta function wouldn’t be appropriate in real life — with its infinities. The charge distribution would be spread out and not just concentrated on one point in space.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">It’s just that when we deal with charged particles, they’re so incredibly small compared to our usual units of measurement, that the particle may as well be treated as though it were infinitely small.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The Dirac delta, however, goes beyond this too. It can be used to find the value of a wave function at a particular point. The delta function is expedient in quantum mechanics. The wave function of a particle gives the probability amplitude of finding a particle within a given region of space. Wave functions are assumed to be elements of the Hilbert space. When the Dirac delta is applied to the wavefunction, it spits out probabilistic values. More importantly, however, it also allows for the existence of the <strong>delta potential:</strong> a potential well mathematically described by the Dirac delta. This can be used to simulate situations where a particle is free to move in two regions of space with a barrier between the two regions. For example, an electron can move almost freely in a conducting material, but if two conducting surfaces are put close together, the interface between them acts as a barrier for the electron that can be approximated by a delta potential.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The Dirac delta is physically impossible but mathematically essential. For a more detailed discussion, check this out by <a style="color:green" href="https://medium.com/u/46693adcc3b7?source=post_page-----4ccd8df313e2--------------------------------" target="_self">Joseph Mellor</a>:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><div class="sketchy"><a href="https://www.cantorsparadise.com/the-road-to-quantum-mechanics-part-7-the-dirac-delta-function-374540fae66e"><h2 style="color:blueviolet; font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:25px;">The Dirac Delta Function</h2><h3 style="color:rgb(45, 34, 54); font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:20px;">The Dirac delta function allows us to model a point source or impulse. Green’s Functions give the response.</h3><p>www.cantorsparadise.com</p></a></div></div></div></div></section><br><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">With that, I will end this here. Thank you for reading!</p></div></div></div></section><?php include_once 'Elemental/footer.php'; ?>